Source: Department of Health and Social Care, Welsh Government, Scottish Government, Northern Ireland Executive.
Cases are reported when lab tests are completed. This may be a few days after initial testing.
Testing capacity is increasing, which is resulting in a greater number of observed cases. There are likely many more cases than currently recorded here.
There may be a small percentage of cases where the same person has had more than one positive test result for COVID-19 in Pillar 2.
DHSC have published explanatory notes to accompany this data:

Hospital Admissions (UK)
Source: NHS England, Welsh Government, Scottish Government, Northern Ireland Executive.
Data are for: NHS trusts and IS providers.

England data captures people admitted to hospital who already had a confirmed COVID-19 status at point of admission, and adds those who tested positive in the previous 24 hours whilst in hospital. Inpatients diagnosed with COVID-19 after admission are assumed to have been admitted on the day prior to their diagnosis.

Wales data includes confirmed and suspected cases, and is the number of admissions to the hospital in the previous 24 hour period up to 9am. The status of COVID/non-COVID is as at the time of reporting not at time of admission.
Northern Ireland data includes suspected and confirmed COVID-19 admissions by admission date.

Data for Scotland provides the profile of admissions into hospital for patients who tested positive for COVID-19 in the 14 days prior to admission to hospital, on the day of their admission or during their stay in hospital. The data are published weekly by Public Health Scotland: https://beta.isdscotland.org/find-publications-and-data/population-health/covid-19/covid-19-statistical-report/
Ventilator beds with COVID-19 patients (UK)
Source: NHS England, Welsh Government, Scottish Government, Northern Ireland Executive.
Overall number of Mechanical Ventilation beds that are occupied by COVID patients, by nation.
This measure includes both Nightingale hospitals and Dragon's Heart/Ysbyty Calon y Ddraig field hospital.
For a ventilator bed to be "available" this requires more than just the physical bed and ventilator.
Wales mechanical ventilator beds cover invasive ventilated beds in a critical care setting, plus those outside of a critical care environment.
Scottish figures include people in ICU with confirmed or suspected COVID-19, and may include a small number of patients who are not on mechanical ventilation.
England figures include the number of COVID-19 patients in beds which are capable of delivering mechanical ventilation.
Northern Ireland figures include the number of COVID-19 patients in beds which are capable of delivering mechanical ventilation.
People in hospital with COVID-19 (UK)
Source: NHS England, Welsh Government, Scottish Government, Northern Ireland Executive.
Data are for NHS Hospital Acute Trusts with a type 1 A&E in England
Fluctuations in the North West have been driven by data validation changes and missing trusts returning data (creating artificial spikes in reporting.)
Nine hospitals, including London Nightingale did not return data for April 9, resulting in a misrepresented drop in hospitalisations.
National data may not be directly comparable as data about COVID-19 patients in hospitals is collected differently across nations.
Community hospitals are included in figures for Wales from 23 April onwards.
England and Scotland data includes 'confirmed' COVID-19 cases; Wales and Northern Ireland data includes ‘confirmed’ and ‘suspected’ COVID-19 cases.
Due to the way Northern Ireland report, the UK figure is calculated by taking the most recent day for Great Britain plus the previous day for Northern Ireland.

From 22nd May, a change in reporting resulted in some patients in Wales being reclassified as COVID patients. Prior to this date, some COVID positive patients who had been in hospital for 14 days and recovered were reported as non COVID patients.
Northern Ireland data were revised on 30 May to reflect a methodology change for calculating the number of COVID inpatients.
Daily COVID-19 deaths confirmed with a positive test (UK)
Source: Department of Health and Social Care, sourced from NHS England, Public Health England and the devolved administrations.
These data can be downloaded here:
https://coronavirus.data.gov.uk/downloads/csv/coronavirus-deaths_latest.csv
7-day rolling average (mean) of daily deaths.
7-day rolling sum of daily deaths is the total of daily deaths for the current day and the six previous days.
UK deaths are reported when paperwork is filed, rather than time of death. Deaths are reported in the 24 hours up to 5pm on the previous day.
Weekly COVID-19 Deaths (UK)
Source: Office for National Statistics, Department of Health and Social Care, sourced from Public Health England and the devolved administrations.
DHSC reporting of UK deaths may lag by up to several days.
DHSC daily counts have been aggregated to weekly totals.
ONS, NRS and NISRA reporting of registered UK deaths is based on information from death certificates.
The ONS average (median) registration delay is four days.
Weekly COVID-19 deaths by place of occurrence (UK)
Source: Office for National Statistics, National Records of Scotland, Northern Ireland Statistics and Research Agency
(COVID-19 deaths include any death where Coronavirus or COVID-19 (suspected or confirmed) was mentioned on the death certificate.)
(Figures are based on date of registration. The ONS average (median) registration delay is four days.   In Scotland, it is three days.  In Northern Ireland, it is five days. )

(England, Wales and Northern Ireland weekly deaths run from Saturday to Friday, Scotland deaths run from Monday to Sunday. Weeks have been aligned to match the ONS method for reporting UK-wide COVID deaths.)

(Non residents are not included in the England and Wales figure to ensure consistency with ONS reporting of UK deaths. For this reason, counts for England and for Wales may not sum to the ONS total for "England and Wales".)

("Other" includes counts from England, Wales and Northern Ireland for Hospices, Communal Establishments (except for Hospitals and Care Homes), and deaths that occurred in settings other than Homes, Hospitals or Care Homes. It includes counts from Scotland for institutions excluding Care Homes and Hospitals.)
(In Scotland, hospices cannot be identified separately. As a result, some fall under the "Hospitals" category and others under "Care Homes".)
(In Scotland, "Home" includes other deaths that did not occur in an institution and these numbers are included in the "Home" category here and on the chart.)
(In Northern Ireland, "Care Home" includes deaths in care homes only. Care home residents who died in a different location will be counted at that location.)
